.TH erpc 3 "kernel 10.6.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
erpc \- Enhanced Remote Procedure Call

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module provide services similar to Remote Procedure Calls. A remote procedure call is a method to call a function on a remote node and collect the answer. It is used for collecting information on a remote node, or for running a function with some specific side effects on the remote node.

.PP
This is an enhanced subset of the operations provided by the \fIrpc\fR module. Enhanced in the sense that it makes it possible to distinguish between returned value, raised exceptions, and other errors. \fIerpc\fR also has better performance and scalability than the original \fIrpc\fR implementation. However, current \fIrpc\fR module will utilize \fIerpc\fR in order to also provide these properties when possible.

.PP
In order for an \fIerpc\fR operation to succeed, the remote node also needs to support \fIerpc\fR. Typically only ordinary Erlang nodes as of OTP 23 have \fIerpc\fR support.

.PP
Note that it is up to the user to ensure that correct code to execute via \fIerpc\fR is available on the involved nodes.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRFor some important information about distributed signals, see the Blocking Signaling Over Distribution section in the \fIProcesses\fR chapter of the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR. Blocking signaling can, for example, cause timeouts in \fIerpc\fR to be significantly delayed.


.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBcall_options() ::\fR
\fB          #{timeout => Timeout :: timeout_time(),\fR
\fB            always_spawn => AlwaysSpawn :: boolean()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Options to be used in \fIcall/3,5\fR and \fImulticall/3,5\fR functions.

timeout
.RS 2
Upper time limit for call operations to complete, see 
\fItimeout_time/0\fR. Default: \fIinfinity\fR.

.RE

always_spawn
.RS 2
If 
\fItrue\fR, the \fIapply()\fR will \fIalways\fR be performed in a freshly spawned process. If \fIfalse\fR, the calling process \fImay\fR be used instead, if possible. Default: \fIfalse\fR.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBcaught_call_exception() ::\fR
\fB          {throw, Throw :: term()} |\fR
\fB          {exit, {exception, Reason :: term()}} |\fR
\fB          {error,\fR
\fB           {exception, Reason :: term(), StackTrace :: [stack_item()]}} |\fR
\fB          {exit, {signal, Reason :: term()}} |\fR
\fB          {error, {erpc, Reason :: term()}}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fB-opaque request_id() \fR

.br
.RS
.PP
An opaque request identifier. For more information see \fIsend_request/4\fR.


.RE
.B
\fB-opaque request_id_collection() \fR

.br
.RS
.PP
An opaque collection of request identifiers (\fIrequest_id/0\fR) where each request identifier can be associated with a label chosen by the user. For more information see \fIreqids_new/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBstack_item() ::\fR
\fB          {Module :: atom(),\fR
\fB           Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB           Arity :: arity() | (Args :: [term()]),\fR
\fB           Location ::\fR
\fB               [{file, Filename :: string()} |\fR
\fB                {line, Line :: pos_integer()}]}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBtimeout_time() :: 0..4294967295 | infinity | {abs, integer()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The timeout time used by erpc functions.

.PP
The value can be:

0..4294967295
.RS 2
Timeout relative to current time in milliseconds.


.RE

infinity
.RS 2
Infinite timeout. That is, the operation will never time out.


.RE

{abs, Timeout}
.RS 2
An absolute Erlang monotonic time timeout in milliseconds. That is, the operation will time out when 
\fIerlang:monotonic_time(millisecond)\fR returns a value larger than or equal to \fITimeout\fR. \fITimeout\fR is not allowed to identify a time further into the future than \fI4294967295\fR milliseconds. Identifying the timeout using an absolute timeout value is especially handy when you have a deadline for responses corresponding to a complete collection of requests (\fIrequest_id_collection/0\fR), since you do not have to recalculate the relative time until the deadline over and over again.

.RE


.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBcall(Node, Fun, TimeoutOrOptions) -> Result\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Node :: node(),\fR
\fB                  Fun :: function(),\fR
\fB                  TimeoutOrOptions :: timeout_time() | call_options(),\fR
\fB                  Result :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIerpc:call(Node, erlang, apply, [Fun,[]], #{timeout => Timeout})\fR.

.PP
May raise all the same exceptions as \fIcall/5\fR plus an \fI{erpc, badarg}\fR \fIerror\fR exception if \fIFun\fR is not a fun of zero arity.


.RE
.B
\fBcall(Node, Module, Function, Args, TimeoutOrOptions) -> Result\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Node :: node(),\fR
\fB                  Module :: atom(),\fR
\fB                  Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                  Args :: [term()],\fR
\fB                  TimeoutOrOptions :: timeout_time() | call_options(),\fR
\fB                  Result :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Evaluates \fIapply(Module, Function, Args)\fR on node \fINode\fR and returns the corresponding value \fIResult\fR.

.PP
\fITimeoutOrOptions\fR can be either a \fItimeout time\fR or a \fIcall options\fR map (since OTP 28.0).

.PP
The \fIcall()\fR function only returns if the applied function successfully returned without raising any uncaught exceptions, the operation did not time out, and no failures occurred. In all other cases an exception is raised. The following exceptions, listed by exception class, can currently be raised by \fIcall()\fR:

throw
.RS 2
The applied function called 
\fIthrow(Value)\fR and did not catch this exception. The exception reason \fIValue\fR equals the argument passed to \fIthrow/1\fR.

.RE

exit
.RS 2
Exception reason:

{exception, ExitReason}
.RS 2
The applied function called 
\fIexit(ExitReason)\fR and did not catch this exception. The exit reason \fIExitReason\fR equals the argument passed to \fIexit/1\fR.

.RE

{signal, ExitReason}
.RS 2
The process that applied the function received an exit signal and terminated due to this signal. The process terminated with exit reason 
\fIExitReason\fR.

.RE


.RE

error
.RS 2
Exception reason:

{exception, ErrorReason, StackTrace}
.RS 2
A runtime error occurred which raised an error exception while applying the function, and the applied function did not catch the exception. The error reason 
\fIErrorReason\fR indicates the type of error that occurred. \fIStackTrace\fR is formatted as when caught in a \fItry/catch\fR construct. The \fIStackTrace\fR is limited to the applied function and functions called by it.

.RE

{erpc, ERpcErrorReason}
.RS 2
The 
\fIerpc\fR operation failed. The following \fIERpcErrorReason\fRs are the most common ones:
badarg
.RS 2
If any one of these are true:


